class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 1) return false; // 0 and negative numbers are not powers of three
        double log = Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);
        return String.valueOf(log).endsWith("0"); // or Math.floor(log) == parseInt(log) (both approaches ensure integer result)
        // Explained: log(3^x) = x * log(3) for any x. So, if the result is an integer, n is a power of three.
    }
}
```

In this code, we calculate the logarithm of the input number with base 3. If the result is an integer, then `n` is a power of three. We convert the result to a string and check if it ends with "0" (a more readable approach), or you can use `Math.floor` and compare with the original log value (a more precise mathematical approach). Both methods ensure we detect only exact powers of three. 

Note: The time complexity is O(1) as logarithm calculation is a constant-time operation in Java (implemented in native code).

